data.content:
Your code **doesn't use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, or catch `ThreadAbortException` — so no Thread.Abort migration is needed. The APIs you use (`Thread.Start`, `.Join`, `.Sleep`) work identically in .NET 8.

That said, the idiomatic .NET 8 approach would be to replace manual threads with `Parallel.ForEachAsync` or `Task.Run`:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, async (item, ct) =>
        {
            await Task.Run(() => Process(item), ct);
        });
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

This gives you built-in `CancellationToken` support (the modern replacement for `Thread.Abort`) and better thread pool utilization. If you do have other code that calls `Thread.Abort`, that will throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8 and needs to be replaced with cooperative cancellation via `CancellationToken`.
